# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: indicators-of-compromise
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] An **advanced persistent threat** (**APT**) is a stealthy cybersecurity threat, typically manipulated by a state or state-sponsored group, which gains unauthorized access to a computer network and remains undetected for an extended period.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] In recent times, the term may also refer to non-state-sponsored groups conducting large-scale targeted intrusions for specific goals.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Such threat actors' motivations are typically political or economic.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Every major business sector has recorded instances of cyberattacks by advanced actors with specific goals, whether to steal, spy, or disrupt.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] These targeted sectors include government, defense, financial services, legal services, industrial, telecoms, consumer goods and many more.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Some groups utilize traditional espionage vectors, including social engineering, human intelligence and infiltration to gain access to a physical location to enable network attacks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The purpose of these attacks is to install custom malware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] APT attacks on mobile devices have also become a legitimate concern, since attackers are able to penetrate into cloud and mobile infrastructure to eavesdrop, steal, and tamper with data.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The median "dwell-time", the time an APT attack goes undetected, differs widely between regions.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] FireEye reported the mean dwell-time for 2018 in the Americas as 71 days, EMEA as 177 days, and APAC as 204 days.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Such a long dwell-time allows attackers a significant amount of time to go through the attack cycle, propagate, and achieve their objectives.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Warnings against targeted, socially-engineered emails dropping trojans to exfiltrate sensitive information were published by UK and US CERT organisations in 2005.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] This method was used throughout the early 1990s and does not in itself constitute an APT.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The term "advanced persistent threat" has been cited as originating from the United States Air Force in 2006 with Colonel Greg Rattray cited as the individual who coined the term.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The Stuxnet computer worm, which targeted the computer hardware of Iran's nuclear program, is one example of an APT attack.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] In this case, the Iranian government might consider the Stuxnet creators to be an advanced persistent threat.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Advanced persistent threat (APT) as a term may be shifting focus to computer-based hacking due to the rising number of occurrences.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] PC World reported an 81 percent increase from 2010 to 2011 of particularly advanced targeted computer attacks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Actors in many countries have used cyberspace as a means to gather intelligence on individuals and groups of individuals of interest.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The United States Cyber Command is tasked with coordinating the US military's offensive and defensive cyber operations.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Numerous sources have alleged that some APT groups are affiliated with, or are agents of, governments of sovereign states.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] A Bell Canada study provided deep research into the anatomy of APTs and uncovered widespread presence in Canadian government and critical infrastructure.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Attribution was established to Chinese and Russian actors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] In incidents analysed by Mandiant, the average period over which the attackers controlled the victim's network was one year, with longest – almost five years.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] The infiltrations were allegedly performed by Shanghai-based Unit 61398 of People's Liberation Army.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Chinese officials have denied any involvement in these attacks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Previous reports from Secdev had previously discovered and implicated Chinese actors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] There are tens of millions of malware variations, which makes it extremely challenging to protect organizations from APT.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] While APT activities are stealthy and hard to detect, the command and control network traffic associated with APT can be detected at the network layer level with sophisticated methods.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Deep log analyses and log correlation from various sources is of limited usefulness in detecting APT activities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] It is challenging to separate noises from legitimate traffic.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Traditional security technology and methods have been ineffective in detecting or mitigating APTs.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Active cyber defense has yielded greater efficacy in detecting and prosecuting APTs (find, fix, finish) when applying cyber threat intelligence to hunt and adversary pursuit activities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Human-Introduced Cyber Vulnerabilities (HICV) are a weak cyber link that are neither well understood nor mitigated, constituting a significant attack vector.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Multiple organizations may assign different names to the same actor.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] As separate researchers could each have their own varying assessments of an APT group, companies such as CrowdStrike, Kaspersky, Mandiant, and Microsoft, among others, have their own internal naming schemes.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Names between different organizations may refer to overlapping but ultimately different groups, based on various data gathered.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] CrowdStrike assigns animals by nation-state or other category, such as "Kitten" for Iran and "Spider" for groups focused on cybercrime.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies have named groups based on this system — Rampant Kitten, for instance, was named by Check Point rather than CrowdStrike.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Dragos bases its names for APT groups on minerals.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Mandiant assigns numbered acronyms in three categories, APT, FIN, and UNC, resulting in APT names like FIN7.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies using a similar system include Proofpoint (TA) and IBM (ITG and Hive).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] Microsoft used to assign names from the periodic table, often stylized in all-caps (e.g.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/advanced-persistent-threat] POTASSIUM); in April 2023, Microsoft changed its naming schema to use weather-based names (e.g.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Sources of cyber threat intelligence include open-source data, social media, operational and technical intelligence, device log files, forensic analysis, internet traffic, as well as data from the dark web and deep web.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern CTI programs stand out from just using raw security data because they combine technical monitoring, outside intelligence sources, and analysis methods to prepare specific and useful assessments about cyber threats aimed at particular organizations or business sectors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analytical interpretation gives context to attackers’ actions, capabilities, and intentions, helping organizations set priorities and allocate security resources effectively.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] When companies base decisions on intelligence and analysis, they can act proactively instead of just reacting to security incidents, stopping breaches before they happen.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] This approach has become increasingly important in recent years, as IBM estimates that exploiting vulnerabilities is the most common way companies are breached, making up 47% of all attacks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The COVID-19 pandemic and the rise in remote work have also contributed to increased vulnerability to threats, making corporate data more exposed.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Due to growing threats on the one hand, and increasing analytical demands on the other, many companies have decided in recent years to outsource their threat analytics tasks to a managed security service provider (MSSP).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cyber threat analytics has also become an important component of modern Security Operations Centers (SOCs), where threat intelligence data is used to enrich alerts, identify malicious infrastructure, and support incident response and threat hunting activities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] There are three categorical levels of cyber threat intelligence: tactical, operational, and strategic.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Each serves a distinct audience and purpose in building a comprehensive threat assessment.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Technical threat analysis focuses on machine-readable indicators of compromise (IoCs): malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control (C2) servers or infrastructure.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] This enables automated detection and response.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] While the conventional distinction is between strategic, tactical, and operational analytics, some large organizations often define technical threat analytics as a separate (fourth) category essential for Security Operations Centers (SOCs).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat analytics platforms also distinguish between indicator-based analytics and behavior-based analytics.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Indicator-based analytics focuses on specific technical artifacts: malicious IP addresses, file hashes, etc.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Behavior-based analytics analyzes attackers’ tactics and techniques to detect threats that may change their infrastructure or indicators over time.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] To obtain effective analytical insights, it is necessary to combine data from internal security tools with external technical and strategic reports to gain a more comprehensive view of the threat landscape.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The process of developing cyber threat intelligence is a circular and continuous process, known as the intelligence cycle, which is composed of five phases, carried out by intelligence teams to provide to leadership relevant and convenient intelligence to reduce danger and uncertainty.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The five phases are: 1) planning and direction; 2) collection; 3) processing; 4) analysis; 5) dissemination.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] In planning and directing, the customer of the intelligence product requests intelligence on a specific topic or objective.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Then, once directed by the client, the second phase begins, collection, which involves accessing the raw information that will be required to produce the finished intelligence product.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Finally, the dissemination phase, in which the newly selected threat intelligence is sent to the various users for their use.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The intelligence cycle model in the field of cyber threat analysis is based on traditional intelligence methods used by military and government intelligence agencies, where structured analysis is employed to transform raw data into the insights needed for decision-making.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cybersecurity researchers also highlight other factors for good threat intelligence, such as accuracy, completeness, timeliness, compatibility, and relevance to the environment where it will be used.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat analytics helps improve threat detection mechanisms by identifying attackers’ methods and behavioral patterns that are not yet detected by automated security monitoring systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Organizations often deploy specialized software known as threat intelligence platforms (TIPs) to aggregate, analyze, and distribute threat intelligence data.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms gather data from both internal and external sources, including security system telemetry, open-source intelligence feeds, malware repositories, vulnerability databases, and reports from security vendors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] By aggregating and correlating indicators of compromise (IoCs) like malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control infrastructure, these platforms help security professionals better understand threat contexts and identify the most significant threats.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] TI platforms are commonly integrated with other cybersecurity systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integrations with tools such as security information and event management (SIEM) systems, endpoint detection and response (EDR) solutions, and incident response platforms enable automated alert enrichment and faster investigation of security incidents.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms also support threat hunting and incident response by organizing indicators and intelligence reports within searchable repositories, allowing analysts to correlate events and identify patterns associated with specific campaigns or threat actors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat intelligence platforms use automated data pipelines and machine learning techniques to process large volumes of threat data and generate analytical insights for proactive cybersecurity strategies.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern programs for collecting and analyzing cyber threat intelligence rely on standardized formats that enable automated exchange between organizations and security tools, as well as the processing of analytical data.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] STIX (Structured Threat Information Expression) is a standardized language for representing analytical information about cyber threats in a machine-readable format, allowing analysts to describe attackers, campaigns, vulnerabilities, and indicators within a structured data model.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Trusted Automated Exchange of Intelligence Information (TAXII) is a protocol for supporting the automated exchange of threat intelligence data, typically used to transmit intelligence in STIX format.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) is widely used in the exchange of threat intelligence to determine how sensitive information is shared among members of trusted communities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analysts use structured analytical models to understand the behavior of attackers and implement defensive measures.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Cyber Kill Chain model, developed by Lockheed Martin, describes the stages of a cyberattack as a linear progression: reconnaissance, weaponization (preparation of attack tools), delivery, exploitation of vulnerabilities, installation, command and control, and actions on objectives.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] This framework helps defenders identify at which stage an attack can be disrupted.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Diamond Model of Intrusion Analysis examines the relationships between four core features of any intrusion event: the adversary, their capabilities (tools and techniques), the infrastructure they use (domains, IP addresses, email addresses), and the victim.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Using these relationships across multiple events, analysts can pivot between incidents, identify patterns, and attribute activity to specific threat actors or campaigns.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The MITRE ATT&CK framework is a knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques based on real-world observations.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] It organizes attacker behavior into 14 tactics (the "why" of an action - initial access, persistence, privilege escalation, defense evasion, etc.), and hundreds of techniques (the "how" - specific methods used to achieve each tactic).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Unlike the linear Cyber Kill Chain, ATT&CK provides a detailed matrix of adversary behaviors that can occur in any order or simultaneously.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Security teams use ATT&CK to map threat intelligence to defensive controls, assess coverage gaps, conduct red team exercises, and build detections aligned with actual adversary tradecraft.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] It has become the de facto standard for describing and sharing operational threat intelligence.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The increasing volume and velocity of cyber threat data have led organizations to automate significant parts of the threat intelligence lifecycle, including data collection, processing, correlation, and distribution.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Automated threat intelligence systems typically ingest data from multiple sources, and then process and correlate this information to identify patterns of malicious activity.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Machine-readable standards and transport protocols (STIX and TAXII) are an important component of automated CTI systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integration between threat intelligence platforms and security operations center (SOC) systems enables automated prioritization of alerts and enrichment of security events using intelligence indicators.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] The drawback of automated analytics systems is that they can generate false positives or rely on low-quality indicators, which means analysts have to verify the results and provide a contextual interpretation.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] For this reason, many organizations adopt a hybrid model in which automated systems perform large-scale data processing while human analysts focus on interpretation, attribution, and strategic assessment of cyber threats.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution is the process of identifying who conducted a cyber attack: the individual actors, organized groups, or nation-state sponsors behind an intrusion.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] In threat intelligence, attribution helps organizations understand adversary intent, prioritize defenses, anticipate future targeting, and inform strategic decisions.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] It also supports law enforcement investigations and policy responses.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] However, attribution is inherently difficult and often remains probabilistic rather than definitive.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attackers routinely employ obfuscation techniques: using proxy infrastructure, VPNs, compromised intermediary systems, and stolen or leased tools.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Advanced threat actors deliberately plant false flags by mimicking the TTPs, language, or infrastructure patterns of other groups to misdirect attribution efforts.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] As a result, different threat intelligence vendors take varying approaches to attribution.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some explicitly attribute threat groups to specific nation-states or sponsoring organizations based on their analysis and confidence thresholds.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Others intentionally avoid geopolitical attribution, instead documenting only observable, undisputable facts, such as language artifacts in malware, shared infrastructure, or technical capabilities, and tracking adversary clusters by neutral designators.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution assessments are typically expressed with varying levels of confidence (low, medium, high) rather than certainty, and erroneous conclusions can have diplomatic, legal, or strategic consequences.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2015 U.S. government legislation in the form of the Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act encouraged the sharing of CTI indicators between government and private organizations.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2016, the U.S. government agency National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a publication (NIST SP 800–150) which further outlined the necessity for Cyber Threat Information Sharing as well as a framework for implementation.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/indicator-of-compromise] An **indicator of compromise** (**IoC**) in computer forensics is an artifact observed on a computer network or within an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/indicator-of-compromise] Common IoCs include virus signatures, suspicious IP addresses, MD5 hashes of malware files, and malicious URLs or domain names associated with botnet command-and-control servers.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/indicator-of-compromise] Once IoCs are identified through incident response or forensic analysis, they can be used for early detection of future attacks with intrusion detection systems and antivirus software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/indicator-of-compromise] Known indicators are often exchanged within the cybersecurity industry, commonly using the Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) to indicate how information may be shared.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/indicator-of-compromise] Other frameworks and standards are also used to support secure information sharing.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware poses serious threats to individuals and businesses on the Internet.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] According to Symantec's 2018 Internet Security Threat Report (ISTR), the number of malware variants increased to 669,947,865 in 2017, which is twice as many malware variants as in 2016.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Cybercrime, which includes malware attacks as well as other crimes committed by computer, was predicted to cost the global economy US$6 trillion in 2021, and is increasing at a rate of 15% per year.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Since 2021, malware has been designed to target computer systems that run critical infrastructure such as the electricity distribution network.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The defense strategies against malware differ according to its type, but most can be prevented by installing antivirus software or firewalls, applying regular patches, securing networks, creating backups, and isolating infected systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware can be designed to evade antivirus software detection algorithms.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The notion of a self-reproducing computer program can be traced back to initial theories about the operation of complex automata.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] John von Neumann showed that in theory a program could reproduce itself.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This constituted a plausibility result in computability theory.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Fred Cohen experimented with computer viruses and confirmed Neumann's postulate and investigated other properties of malware such as detectability and self-obfuscation using rudimentary encryption.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] His 1987 doctoral dissertation was on the subject of computer viruses.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The combination of cryptographic technology as part of the payload of the virus, exploiting it for attack purposes was initialized and investigated from the mid-1990s, and includes initial ransomware and evasion ideas.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Before Internet access became widespread, viruses spread on personal computers by infecting executable programs or boot sectors of floppy disks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] By inserting a copy of itself into the machine code instructions in these programs or boot sectors, a virus causes itself to be run whenever the program is run or the disk is booted.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Early computer viruses were written for the Apple II and Mac, but they became more widespread with the dominance of the IBM PC and MS-DOS.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The first IBM PC virus in the wild was a boot sector virus dubbed (c)Brain, created in 1986 by the Farooq Alvi brothers in Pakistan.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware distributors would trick the user into booting or running from an infected device or medium.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, a virus could make an infected computer add autorunnable code to any USB stick plugged into it.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Anyone who then attached the stick to another computer set to autorun from USB would in turn become infected, and also pass on the infection in the same way.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Older email software would automatically open HTML email containing potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Users may also execute disguised malicious email attachments.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The *2018 Data Breach Investigations Report* by Verizon, cited by CSO Online, states that emails are the primary method of malware delivery, accounting for 96% of malware delivery around the world.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The first worms, network-borne infectious programs, originated not on personal computers, but on multitasking Unix systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The first well-known worm was the Morris worm of 1988, which infected SunOS and VAX BSD systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Unlike a virus, this worm did not insert itself into other programs.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Instead, it exploited security holes (vulnerabilities) in network server programs and started itself running as a separate process.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This same behavior is used by today's worms as well.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] With the rise of the Microsoft Windows platform in the 1990s, and the flexible macros of its applications, it became possible to write infectious code in the macro language of Microsoft Word and similar programs.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] These *macro viruses* infect documents and templates rather than applications (executables), but rely on the fact that macros in a Word document are a form of executable code.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Many early infectious programs, including the Morris Worm, the first internet worm, were written as experiments or pranks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Today, malware is used by both black hat hackers and governments to steal personal, financial, or business information.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Today, any device that plugs into a USB port – even lights, fans, speakers, toys, or peripherals such as a digital microscope – can be used to spread malware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Devices can be infected during manufacturing or supply if quality control is inadequate.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Since the rise of widespread broadband Internet access, malicious software has more frequently been designed for profit.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Since 2003, the majority of widespread viruses and worms have been designed to take control of users' computers for illicit purposes.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Infected "zombie computers" can be used to send email spam, to host contraband data such as child pornography, or to engage in distributed denial-of-service attacks as a form of extortion.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware is used broadly against government or corporate websites to gather sensitive information, or to disrupt their operation in general.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Further, malware can be used against individuals to gain information such as personal identification numbers or details, bank or credit card numbers, and passwords.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Beyond its use in criminal enterprises, malware has also been deployed as a tool for sabotage, often driven by political objectives.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A notable example is Stuxnet, which was engineered to interfere with specific industrial control systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] In other cases, politically motivated malware attacks have targeted entire networks, causing widespread disruption.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] In 2024, a botnet owner was arrested for engaging in a pay-per-install operation for financial gain.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware can be classified in numerous ways, and certain malicious programs may fall into two or more categories simultaneously.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Broadly, software can be categorised into three types: (i) goodware; (ii) grayware and (iii) malware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A computer virus is software usually hidden within another seemingly harmless program that can produce copies of itself and insert them into other programs or files, and that usually performs a harmful action (such as destroying data).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] They have been likened to biological viruses.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] An example of this is a portable execution infection, a technique, usually used to spread malware, that inserts extra data or executable code into PE files.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A computer virus is software that embeds itself in some other executable software (including the operating system itself) on the target system without the user's knowledge and consent and when it is run, the virus is spread to other executable files.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A worm is a stand-alone malware software that *actively* transmits itself over a network to infect other computers and can copy itself without infecting files.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] These definitions lead to the observation that a virus requires the user to run an infected software or operating system for the virus to spread, whereas a worm spreads itself.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Once malicious software is installed on a system, it is essential that it stays concealed, to avoid detection.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Software packages known as *rootkits* allow this concealment, by modifying the host's operating system so that the malware is hidden from the user.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Rootkits can prevent a harmful process from being visible in the system's list of processes, or keep its files from being read.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some types of harmful software contain routines to evade identification or removal attempts, not merely to hide themselves.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A backdoor is a broad term for a computer program that allows an attacker persistent unauthorised remote access to a victim's machine often without their knowledge.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The attacker typically uses another attack (such as a trojan, worm or virus) to bypass authentication mechanisms usually over an unsecured network such as the Internet to install the backdoor application.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A backdoor can also be a side effect of a software bug in legitimate software that is exploited by an attacker to gain access to a victim's computer or network.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The idea has often been suggested that computer manufacturers preinstall backdoors on their systems to provide technical support for customers, but this has never been reliably verified.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Backdoors may be installed by Trojan horses, worms, implants, or other methods.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A Trojan horse misrepresents itself to masquerade as a regular, benign program or utility in order to persuade a victim to install it.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A Trojan horse usually carries a hidden destructive function that is activated when the application is started.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The term is derived from the Ancient Greek story of the Trojan horse used to invade the city of Troy by stealth.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Trojan horses are generally spread by some form of social engineering, for example, where a user is duped into executing an email attachment disguised to be unsuspicious, (e.g., a routine form to be filled in), or by drive-by download.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] While Trojan horses and backdoors are not easily detectable by themselves, computers may appear to run slower, emit more heat or fan noise due to heavy processor or network usage, as may occur when cryptomining software is installed.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Cryptominers may limit resource usage or only run during idle times in an attempt to evade detection.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Unlike computer viruses and worms, Trojan horses generally do not attempt to inject themselves into other files or otherwise propagate themselves.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Modern Trojans are often disguised within legitimate-looking applications, making them particularly effective at bypassing basic user awareness and simple antivirus measures.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] In spring 2017, Mac users were hit by the new version of Proton Remote Access Trojan (RAT) trained to extract password data from various sources, such as browser auto-fill data, the Mac-OS keychain, and password vaults.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Droppers are a sub-type of Trojans that solely aim to deliver malware upon the system that they infect with the desire to subvert detection through stealth and a light payload.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It is important not to confuse a dropper with a loader or stager.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A loader or stager will merely load an extension of the malware (for example a collection of malicious functions through reflective dynamic link library injection) into memory.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The purpose is to keep the initial stage light and undetectable.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A dropper merely downloads further malware to the system.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Ransomware prevents a user from accessing their files until a ransom is paid.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] There are two variations of ransomware, being crypto ransomware and locker ransomware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Locker ransomware just locks down a computer system without encrypting its contents, whereas crypto ransomware locks down a system and encrypts its contents.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, programs such as CryptoLocker encrypt files securely, and only decrypt them on payment of a substantial sum of money.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Lock-screens, or screen lockers is a type of "cyber police" ransomware that blocks screens on Windows or Android devices with a false accusation in harvesting illegal content, trying to scare the victims into paying up a fee.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Jisut and SLocker impact Android devices more than other lock-screens, with Jisut making up nearly 60 percent of all Android ransomware detections.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Encryption-based ransomware, like the name suggests, is a type of ransomware that encrypts all files on an infected machine.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] These types of malware then display a pop-up ad informing the user that their files have been encrypted and that they must pay (usually in Bitcoin) to recover them.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some examples of encryption-based ransomware are CryptoLocker and WannaCry.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some malware is used to generate money by click fraud, making it appear that the computer user has clicked an advertising link on a site, generating a payment from the advertiser.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It was estimated in 2012 that about 60 to 70% of all active malware used some kind of click fraud, and 22% of all ad-clicks were fraudulent.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Grayware is any unwanted application or file that can worsen the performance of computers and may cause security risks but which there is insufficient consensus or data to classify them as malware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Types of grayware typically include spyware, adware, fraudulent dialers, joke programs ("jokeware") and remote access tools.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, at one point, Sony BMG compact discs silently installed a rootkit on purchasers' computers with the intention of preventing illicit copying.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Potentially unwanted programs (PUPs) are applications that would be considered unwanted despite often being intentionally downloaded by the user.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] PUPs include spyware, adware, and fraudulent dialers.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Many security products classify unauthorised key generators as PUPs, although they frequently carry true malware in addition to their ostensible purpose.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] (2012) estimated that as much as 55% of key generators could contain malware and that about 36% malicious key generators were not detected by antivirus software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some types of adware turn off anti-malware and virus protection; technical remedies are available.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Programs designed to monitor users' web browsing, display unsolicited advertisements, or redirect affiliate marketing revenues are called spyware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Spyware programs do not spread like viruses; instead they are generally installed by exploiting security holes.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] They can also be hidden and packaged together with unrelated user-installed software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The Sony BMG rootkit was intended to prevent illicit copying; but also reported on users' listening habits, and unintentionally created extra security vulnerabilities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Antivirus software typically uses two techniques to detect malware: (i) static analysis and (ii) dynamic/heuristic analysis.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Static analysis involves studying the software code of a potentially malicious program and producing a signature of that program.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This information is then used to compare scanned files by an antivirus program.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Because this approach is not useful for malware that has not yet been studied, antivirus software can use dynamic analysis to monitor how the program runs on a computer and block it if it performs unexpected activity.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The aim of any malware is to conceal itself from detection by users or antivirus software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Detecting potential malware is difficult for two reasons.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The first is that it is difficult to determine if software is malicious.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The second is that malware uses technical measures to make it more difficult to detect it.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] An estimated 33% of malware is not detected by antivirus software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The most commonly employed anti-detection technique involves encrypting the malware payload in order to prevent antivirus software from recognizing the signature.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Tools such as crypters come with an encrypted blob of malicious code and a decryption stub.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The stub decrypts the blob and loads it into memory.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Because antivirus does not typically scan memory and only scans files on the drive, this allows the malware to evade detection.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Advanced malware has the ability to transform itself into different variations, making it less likely to be detected due to the differences in its signatures.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Other common techniques used to evade detection include, from common to uncommon: (1) evasion of analysis and detection by fingerprinting the environment when executed; (2) confusing automated tools' detection methods.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This allows malware to avoid detection by technologies such as signature-based antivirus software by changing the server used by the malware; (3) timing-based evasion.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The use of existing binaries to carry out malicious activities is a technique known as LotL, or Living off the Land.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This reduces the amount of forensic artifacts available to analyze.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Recently these types of attacks have become more frequent with a 432% increase in 2017 and makeup 35% of the attacks in 2018.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Such attacks are not easy to perform but are becoming more prevalent with the help of exploit-kits.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A vulnerability is a weakness, flaw or software bug in an application, a complete computer, an operating system, or a computer network that is exploited by malware to bypass defences or gain privileges it requires to run.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, TestDisk 6.4 or earlier contained a vulnerability that allowed attackers to inject code into Windows.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, a common method is exploitation of a buffer overrun vulnerability, where software designed to store data in a specified region of memory does not prevent more data than the buffer can accommodate from being supplied.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware may provide data that overflows the buffer, with malicious executable code or data after the end; when this payload is accessed it does what the attacker, not the legitimate software, determines.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware can exploit recently discovered vulnerabilities before developers have had time to release a suitable patch.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Even when new patches addressing the vulnerability have been released, they may not necessarily be installed immediately, allowing malware to take advantage of systems lacking patches.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Sometimes even applying patches or installing new versions does not automatically uninstall the old versions.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] There are several ways the users can stay informed and protected from security vulnerabilities in software.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Software providers often announce updates that address security issues.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Common vulnerabilities are assigned unique identifiers (CVE IDs) and listed in public databases like the National Vulnerability Database.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Tools like Secunia PSI, free for personal use, can scan a computer for outdated software with known vulnerabilities and attempt to update them.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Firewalls and intrusion prevention systems can monitor the network traffic for suspicious activity that might indicate an attack.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Users and programs can be assigned more privileges than they require, and malware can take advantage of this.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, of 940 Android apps sampled, one third of them asked for more privileges than they required.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Apps targeting the Android platform can be a major source of malware infection but one solution is to use third-party software to detect apps that have been assigned excessive privileges.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some systems allow all users to make changes to the core components or settings of the system, which is considered over-privileged access today.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This was the standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems, where there was no distinction between an *administrator* or *root*, and a regular user of the system.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] In some systems, non-administrator users are over-privileged by design, in the sense that they are allowed to modify internal structures of the system.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] In some environments, users are over-privileged because they have been inappropriately granted administrator or equivalent status.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This can be because users tend to demand more privileges than they need, so often end up being assigned unnecessary privileges.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Some systems allow code executed by a user to access all rights of that user, which is known as over-privileged code.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This was also standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Malware, running as over-privileged code, can use this privilege to subvert the system.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Almost all currently popular operating systems, and also many scripting applications allow code too many privileges, usually in the sense that when a user executes code, the system allows that code all rights of that user.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] A credential attack occurs when a user account with administrative privileges is cracked and that account is used to provide malware with appropriate privileges.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Typically, the attack succeeds because the weakest form of account security is used, which is typically a short password that can be cracked using a dictionary or brute force attack.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Using strong passwords and enabling two-factor authentication can reduce this risk.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] With the latter enabled, even if an attacker can crack the password, they cannot use the account without also having the token possessed by the legitimate user of that account.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It is estimated that approximately 83% of malware infections between January and March 2020 were spread via systems running Windows 10.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This risk is mitigated by segmenting the networks into different subnetworks and setting up firewalls to block traffic between them.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Anti-malware (sometimes also called antivirus) programs block and remove some or all types of malware.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] For example, Microsoft Security Essentials (for Windows XP, Vista, and Windows 7) and Windows Defender (for Windows 8, 10 and 11) provide real-time protection.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] The Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool removes malicious software from the system.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Additionally, several capable antivirus software programs are available for free download from the Internet (usually restricted to non-commercial use).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Tests found some free programs to be competitive with commercial ones.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] **Removal:** Anti-malware software programs can be used solely for detection and removal of malware software that has already been installed onto a computer.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] **Sandboxing:** Sandboxing confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations and isolating them from other applications on the host while limiting access to system resources.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Browser sandboxing isolates web processes to prevent malware and exploits, enhancing security.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Any time the operating system accesses a file, the on-access scanner checks if the file is infected or not.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Typically, when an infected file is found, execution is stopped and the file is quarantined to prevent further damage with the intention to prevent irreversible system damage.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Most AVs allow users to override this behaviour.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] This can have a considerable performance impact on the operating system, though the degree of impact is dependent on how many pages it creates in virtual memory.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Sandboxing is a security model that confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations to authorized "safe" actions and isolating them from other applications on the host.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It also limits access to system resources like memory and the file system to maintain isolation.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Browser sandboxing is a security measure that isolates web browser processes and tabs from the operating system to prevent malicious code from exploiting vulnerabilities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It helps protect against malware, zero-day exploits, and unintentional data leaks by trapping potentially harmful code within the sandbox.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] It involves creating separate processes, limiting access to system resources, running web content in isolated processes, monitoring system calls, and memory constraints.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Inter-process communication (IPC) is used for secure communication between processes.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Escaping the sandbox involves targeting vulnerabilities in the sandbox mechanism or the operating system's sandboxing features.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] While sandboxing is not foolproof, it significantly reduces the attack surface of common threats.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Keeping browsers and operating systems updated is crucial to mitigate vulnerabilities.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Website vulnerability scans check the website, detect malware, may note outdated software, and may report known security issues, in order to reduce the risk of the site being compromised.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Structuring a network as a set of smaller networks, and limiting the flow of traffic between them to that known to be legitimate, can hinder the ability of infectious malware to replicate itself across the wider network.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Software-defined networking provides techniques to implement such controls.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] However, malware can still cross the air gap in some situations, not least due to the need to introduce software into the air-gapped network and can damage the availability or integrity of assets thereon.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Stuxnet is an example of malware that is introduced to the target environment via a USB drive, causing damage to processes supported on the environment without the need to exfiltrate data.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] AirHopper, BitWhisper, GSMem and Fansmitter are four techniques introduced by researchers that can leak data from air-gapped computers using electromagnetic, thermal and acoustic emissions.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] Utilizing bibliometric analysis, the study of malware research trends from 2005 to 2015, considering criteria such as impact journals, highly cited articles, research areas, number of publications, keyword frequency, institutions, and authors, revealed an annual growth rate of 34.1%.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] North America led in research output, followed by Asia and Europe.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/malware] China and India were identified as emerging contributors.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The STIX fonts are available as fully hinted OpenType/CFF fonts.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The project was initiated in 1995 and officially released its first stable version (STIX 1.0) in May 2010, after 15 years of development, with subsequent updates including STIX Two released in 2016.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] There is currently no TrueType version of the STIX fonts available, but the STIX Mission Statement includes the intention to create one in the future.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] However, there exists an unofficial conversion of STIX Fonts (from the beta version release) to TrueType, suitable for use with software without OpenType support.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] STIX fonts also include natural language glyphs for Latin, Greek and Cyrillic.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The family is designed to be visually compatible with the Times New Roman family, a popular choice in book publishing.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Among the glyphs in STIX, 32.9% have been contributed by the project members.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The commercial TeX vendor and TeX font foundry MicroPress has been contracted to create the additional glyphs.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The STIX project will also create a TeX implementation.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Goals also include incorporating the characters into Unicode, and ensuring that browsers can use them.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Members of the STIX Fonts project, known collectively as the STI Pub consortium, include the American Institute of Physics, the American Chemical Society, the American Mathematical Society, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the American Physical Society, and Elsevier.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] A beta version of the fonts was released on October 31, 2007.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] This version does not include enough of the OpenType mathematical layout features present in Cambria Math, so it is not usable to the fullest extent in Microsoft Office 2007.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The Latin glyph set included in the beta version does not yet cover all the characters required to typeset in Eastern European languages.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] "Final design changes" were declared "complete" at the project website on June 9, 2008.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] A release by end of May 2009 for the "initial production release" was announced, still without the support for OpenType layout features of Office 2007 or TeX.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] In September 2009, the fonts went to the final packaging stage.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] However, in October, missing glyphs were discovered, adding a delay.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The fonts were scheduled to be released in April 2010, and released on May 28, 2010.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The project has taken considerably longer than forecast.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The website has been updated only intermittently, and thus has regularly been out-of-date, with forecast milestones often being overshot.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] This version facilitates equation editing in recent versions of Microsoft Word.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Version 1.1.0 with LaTeX support was released on May 29, 2013.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] On December 1, 2016, the official project website announced the release of STIX version 2.0.0.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] This was created by Ross Mills and John Hudson of Tiro Typeworks.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Unlike the previous version, which closely matches Nimbus Roman No.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] 9 L, it is an original design loosely inspired by a smaller 10 point size of Times New Roman, with a higher x-height.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] In April 2018, the Type 1 version of the STIX Two fonts for use in LaTeX was released.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] At the same time, the STIX project hosting platform has been migrated to GitHub (https://github.com/stipub/stixfonts/).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The STIX Fonts are included in OS X in versions from Lion (10.7) onwards.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The JavaScript framework MathJax uses the STIX fonts for including mathematics in web pages.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] Installing the fonts on the local computer improves MathJax's typesetting speed.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] The Math Editor equation editor uses STIX fonts as its primary font.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] A precursor to the STIX project is the ESSTIX (Elsevier Science STIX) font, developed and later donated by Elsevier.
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] It is currently available from the World Wide Web Consortium as part of the Amaya (web browser).
[src:indicators-of-compromise/stix] However, the STIX fonts are not used in most of the peer-reviewed journals published by Elsevier.
